## How the algorithm works — key design decisions

### Why `findIndex` + `slice` instead of a `while` loop
Timestamps are always appended in real time, so the array is naturally sorted ascending. All stale entries sit at the *front*, meaning one `findIndex` locates the cutoff boundary in a single pass. `slice(firstValid)` then hands back a new array without mutating the original (safe if the same reference were ever read concurrently). A `while`-pop loop would be equally correct but mutates in place and is harder to follow.

### Why check count *before* pushing
The limit means "no more than N requests in any rolling window." If we pushed first we'd allow the (N+1)-th request before detecting the breach. Checking first means the stored count is always the true number of *permitted* calls.

### `X-RateLimit-Reset` semantics
`timestamps[0]` is the oldest in-window timestamp. It exits the window at `timestamps[0] + windowMs`, which is the earliest moment a new slot opens. For a client sitting exactly at the limit, this equals what `Retry-After` would have returned — consistent information on both the allowed and rejected paths.

### `cleanupTimer.unref()`
Without `.unref()`, Node's event loop stays alive as long as the `setInterval` is active. This causes test suites to hang and lambda/container runtimes to incur idle billing. `.unref()` marks the timer as non-blocking while still letting it fire when the loop is otherwise busy.

### `Retry-After` on 429
`timestamps[0] + windowMs - now` is always strictly positive because `timestamps[0]` survived the `> cutoff` filter, meaning `timestamps[0] > now - windowMs`, i.e. `timestamps[0] + windowMs > now`. No clamping needed.

